		<body>
			<pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-JMP002_01.jpg"/>
			<p rend="letter-spacing: +2px">Statement</p>

			<p>written with <persName ref="#ehri_et_steiner_zdenek">Zdeněk</persName> and <persName ref="#ehri_et_steiner_jiri">Jiří <hi
						rend="letter-spacing: +2px">Steiner</hi></persName>, born <date when="1929-05-20">20. 5. 1929</date> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName>, residents of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName>, former <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483">prisoners</term> in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">concentration camps</term> of <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto">Theresienstadt</placeName> and <placeName type="camp"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-0">Auschwitz</placeName>, residing in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague XI.</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Vratislavova</placeName> 13, <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_czechs">Czech</term> nationality.</p>

			<p>We <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">left</term> <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> bound for <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto">Theresienstadt</placeName> on <date when="1942-12-22"
					>22. 12. 1942</date> together with our <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819"
					>parents</term> and a great number of <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819"
					>relatives</term>. We spent 8½ months <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto"
					>Theresienstadt</placeName>, where things had been so-so for us. We <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-267" type="subject">left</term> <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto">Theresienstadt</placeName> on <date when="1943-09-06"
					>September 6th, 1943</date>, and, after a miserable two-day journey, we finally arrived at the Neu-Berun train station. From
				there, they took us to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">concentration camp</term>
					in <placeName type="camp" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Birkenau</placeName>. We were told that it
				was only a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-168" type="subject">quarantine</term>. After
				the usual procedures, such as a bath and a getting a tattoo (we were given the numbers 147742 and 147743), we were clothed in old
					<term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836">rags</term> (<term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term> in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">adult</term>
				<term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836">clothing</term>) and <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837">housed</term> in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-594" type="subject">camp B II b</term>, where we spent 6
				whole months. We experienced so much in this place. Through the efforts of <persName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/terezin-victims-person-iti-1459810" type="victim">Fredy Hirsch</persName>, a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-595" type="subject">children’s home</term> was established.
				We <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term> were better off than the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">adults</term> because we didn’t have to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>, our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> was a little bit better, and, later, our
					<term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836">clothes</term> were better as well. Such was our
				life in the <placeName type="camp" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Birkenau</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-595" type="subject">children’s camp</term> under
				extremely harsh <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831">conditions</term>. A <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-287" type="subject">doctor</term> arrived in <date when="1943-12"
					>December</date> (each <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567">camp</term> had a <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491">building</term> for the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">sick</term> and a single German <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-287" type="subject">doctor</term>, who generally didn’t know how to do
				much else besides sending as many people as possible to their graves, served several of these <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491">buildings</term>). With a wave of his fingers, Dr. <persName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000569">Mengele</persName> decided who lived and who died, just like
				Nero did in ancient times. This renowned <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-287" type="subject"
					>doctor</term> was very interested in us <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-495"
					>twins</term>, which was actually what saved us despite the fact that we came down with so many <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292">illnesses</term>. Once, Dr. <persName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000569">Mengele</persName> took a closer look at us, but then he <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">contracted</term> spotted <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-493" type="subject">typhus</term>. In addition to him, we were tortured by
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SSman</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_buntrock_fritz">Buntrock</persName>, who had a preference for beating <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term>. Another <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SSman</term>, probably a <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_russians">Russian</term> spy, who helped one of our people <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escape</term>, was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject">shot</term> by other <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS officers</term> after he returned.</p>


			<p>In the meantime, the fateful month of <date when="1944-03">March</date> began. This month took away our <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819">parents</term> and all of our closest friends — the only thing that
				we still had in our lives. At the start of the <date when="1944-03">month</date>, it was rumored that the entire <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-267" type="subject">transport</term> that had arrived in
					<date when="1943-09">September 1943</date> would be taken to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">labor camp</term> in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-places-place-iti-211">Heidebreck</placeName>. And that’s exactly what
				happened. On <date when="1944-03-05">March 5th</date>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-716" type="subject">postcards</term> on which we were
				supposed to write to our relatives that we were healthy and doing fine were handed out. These <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-716" type="subject">cards</term> were sent dated <date
					when="1944-03-25">March 25</date>th-<date when="1944-03-27">27</date>th. We weren’t allowed to write about our departure. On the
				morning of <date when="1944-03-06">March 6th</date>, as usual: <q><foreign xml:lang="de">Blockälteste antreten</foreign></q> — an
				order for the entire <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521">transport</term> to go to the
				lower section of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term> immediately. From
				there they took us to <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496">camp</term>
				<placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">B II a</placeName>. There were so many rumors going about, for
				example that it wasn’t a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">labor transport</term>, but
				a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-499" type="subject">chimney</term>. We didn’t believe it because we
				thought it was impossible. We waited all day, and in the evening we were told that the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521">transport</term> couldn’t depart because 100 <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483">persons</term> were to be <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-148" type="subject">reclaimed</term>. This news greatly
				disturbed us. A terrible sleepless night wreaked havoc with our nerves. The <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483">people</term>, who were now extremely distraught, didn’t pay
				attention to anything; everyone just wished for this uncertainty to end. Midday, on <date when="1944-03-07">March 7th</date>, a call:
						<q><foreign xml:lang="de">Ordnung am Block, Raportführer <persName ref="#ehri_et_buntrock_fritz">Buntrok</persName>
						geht.</foreign></q> And he really came, read the names of several <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-287" type="subject">doctors</term>, and then we heard our names. We became
				very frightened, because <persName ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/126948-pavel-steiner/" type="victim"
					>father's</persName> name wasn’t read, and <persName ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/126732-jana-steinerova/"
					type="victim">mother</persName> wasn’t present on the block. <persName ref="#ehri_et_buntrock_fritz">Buntrok</persName> assured
					<persName ref="http://www.holocaust.cz/databaze-obeti/obet/126948-pavel-steiner/" type="victim">father</persName> that we would
				see one another in the evening, and we were taken to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491"
					type="subject">Krankenbau</term> of <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496">camp</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-594" type="subject">B II b</term>. There, we found out
				what it was really all about. There were 32 of us in total, <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-495">twins</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-287" type="subject">doctors</term> combined. <persName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000569">Mengele</persName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-148" type="subject">reclaimed</term> us <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-495">twins</term> because he was interested in us, as we’ve
				already mentioned. He came to see us the next day. When we told him that our <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819">parents</term> had left on the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521">transport</term>, he said: <q><foreign xml:lang="de"
					>Schade</foreign></q>. In the meantime, we found out that the cars had driven off during the night ¨ <pb n="2"
					facs="EHRI-ET-JMP002_02.jpg"/> in the direction of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501"
					type="subject">crematorium</term>. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-594"
					type="subject">camp</term> was empty; flames shot up from the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501"
					type="subject">crematorium</term>. We will never forget this scene. But we didn’t believe that our <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819">parents</term> were <term type="subejct"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745">dead</term>. However, we soon found out the truth from a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-287" type="subject">doctor</term> who was a member of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1391" type="subject">Sonderkommando</term>, who was forced to do this
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>. <persName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000569">Mengele</persName> arrived the following day, and took us by car
				to the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Roma camp</placeName>, which was where his station was.
				There, he precisely measured and weighed us, measured the length and width of our fingers and nails, the length and width of our
				noses, and anything else that could be measured and weighed. He also took down the color of our hair and skin. He carefully inspected
				us. He took fingerprints of our hands and feet. He worked alone; he never entrusted anyone else with the tasks he was performing. Then
				they brought us to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491" type="subject">Krankenbau</term> and life
				went on. We received 2 liters of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term> per
				day, otherwise the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> was the same as
				before. We were also photographed and x-rayed. Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-287"
					type="subject">doctors</term>, who guaranteed the correctness of the examinations with their lives, had to examine our nerves,
				eyes, teeth, and ears.</p>

			<p>The first <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">labor</term>
				<term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521">transport</term> from <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496">camp</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-594" type="subject">B II b</term> left on <date
					when="1944-07-01">1. 7.</date> In the meantime, another <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-267" type="subject">transport</term> from <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto">Theresienstadt</placeName> with 7½ thousand <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483">people</term> arrived in <date when="1944-05"
					>May</date>. This brought the number of <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483"
					>people</term> in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-594" type="subject">camp</term>
				to 12,500, 3,000 of whom left to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>. The
				rest were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501" type="subject">incinerated</term> within 2 nights. We
				were taken to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2" type="camp">B II f</placeName>. In this new
					<placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">camp</placeName>, they <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-495" type="subject">drew our blood</term>, which made our weakened bodies
				feel even worse. There is one horrible experience that we will never forget: one of our torturers, the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496">camp</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-287" type="subject">doctor</term>
				<persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-001165">Thilo</persName>, was making a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">selection</term>, i.e. choosing the <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483">people</term> who would be sent to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501" type="subject">crematorium</term>, and he took our names down. What
				we felt when he did this cannot be described. Fortunately, <persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000569"
					>Mengele</persName> heard this and saved us because he still needed us.</p>


			<p>The front was approaching and the mood in the <placeName type="camp" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2"
					>camp</placeName> lifted. During this time, I became a <distinct type="camp_language">Pipel</distinct> in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491" type="subject">Krankenbau</term>, i.e. a runner, and so I was
				slightly better off. But then came winter and a new year, which was happier because we could hear the thunder of cannons. A rumor went
				around that the <placeName type="camp" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">camp</placeName> was going to be
				liquidated, but nothing happened. Finally, on <date when="1945-01-16">January 16th</date>, they led the first <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-517" type="subject">transport on foot</term> out of <placeName type="camp"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2">Birkenau</placeName>. The following days were extremely vexing, because
				one <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521">transport</term> after another departed.
				Everyone left voluntarily and we <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term>
				were the last to leave, partly because we didn’t want to go. People had to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-517" type="subject">walk</term> 60 km in the cold and frost, poorly <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836">clothed</term> and <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569">hungry</term>. We expected to be told that <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522">trains</term> would come pick us up. We finally got what we wanted on
					<date when="1945-01-20">January 20th</date>, the day the last <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216"
					type="subject">SSman</term> left the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2" type="camp"
					>camp</placeName>. This was a wonderful time for us. We went wherever we wanted, <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832">ate</term> whatever we wanted, did whatever we felt like doing. We
				roamed around the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term> camp. In short, we were
				having a great time. We went without supervision for 5 days. Then, a group of SDmen arrived. They wanted to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject">do us in</term>, but didn’t get the chance. They, too,
				fled, and so we stayed until <date when="1945-01-27">January 27th</date>, when the victorious <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583">Red Army</orgName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">took over</term>.</p>

			<p>On <date when="1945-03-27">March 27th</date>, the <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_czechs">Czech</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-779" type="subject">Svoboda’s Army</term> took charge of
				us and brought us to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName>. Out of our <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819">family</term> of 18, only 3 of us survived.</p>

